<font color="#FF0000">ANOTHER RESPONSE</font><br>
<tt>Sun May 25  3:52:33 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
To EVERY VN Vet Who Reads this - Thanks &amp; Welcome HOME!<br><br>
Dear Dr. Spatz, <br><br>
None of us HAD to go to 'Nam? I beg your pardon! I enlisted in 1965, I was sent to Okinawa six months later. On Oki I sought the &quot;HELP&quot; of a service Psychiatrist for Gender Dysphoria. After a year of therapy he helped - he had me transfered to the 'Nam as a cure! Big choice. I<br>
experienced that horror - learned I could kill, learned I could hate. You and many others did what you considered right and I honor that but let's NOT FORGET the sacrifices made over there; the 58,000 AMERICAN lives wasted, the<br>
stolen youth and innocense - the purity - of all who served. It is we who HAD to be there, we who feel guilty about coming back while other's did not, we who bear the RAGE, the heart-wrenching pain of having to remember, of having night- mares, the physical quaking and flood of tears.<br><br>
I am not ashamed of my service - I am ashamed for surviving and detest that I am not &quot;acceptable&quot; to even be in a PTSD group.
<p><code>-- dulcinea@accesscom.net  (Katherine Rosen) </code><p>


